n<p>This is the protocol from Qiagen.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>E. coli strains can also be stored for up to 1 year as stabs in soft\n  agar. Stab cultures are used to transport or send bacterial strains to\n  other labs. Prepare stab cultures as follows:<\/p>\n  \n  <ol>\n  <li><p>Prepare and autoclave LB agar (standard LB medium containing 0.7% agar) as described in the last issue of QIAGEN News (1).<\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p>Cool the LB agar to below 50°C (when you can hold it comfortably) and add the appropriate antibiotic(s). While the agar is still liquid,\n  add 1 ml agar to a 2-ml screw-cap vial under sterile conditions, then\n  leave to solidify.<\/p><\/li>\n  <\/ol>\n  \n  <p>Vials of agar can be prepared in batches and stored at room\n  temperature until required.<\/p>\n  \n  <ol>\n  <li>Using a sterile straight wire, pick a single colony from a freshly streaked plate and stab it deep down into the soft agar several times\n  (Figure 1).<\/li>\n  <\/ol>\n  \n  <p>￼￼￼￼￼￼￼￼￼4. Incubate the vial at 37°C for 8\u201312 h leaving the cap\n  slightly loose.<\/p>\n  \n  <ol>\n  <li>Seal the vial tightly and store in the dark, preferably at 4°C.<\/li>\n  <\/ol>\n  \n  <p>When recovering a stored strain, it is advisable to check the\n  antibiotic markers by streaking the strain onto a selective plate.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>I believe if the shipping is &lt;24hrs you could send a stab in ice.<\/p>\n\n<p>Hope that helps<\/p>\n\n<p>Ben<\/p>\n","answer_id":2782,"question_id":2778,"up_vote_count":5}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2778/what-is-the-appropriate-method-to-send-a-strain","last_activity_date":1340893453,"creation_date":1340853697,"answer_count":2,"title":"What is the appropriate method to send a strain?","body":"<p>We are planning to send an ecoli strain to another lab. What is the appropriate way to do so. No MTA is required but the options seem to be using filter paper or sending a glycerol stock on dry ice.<\/p>\n","question_id":2778,"tags":["ecoli"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":2782,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":4862,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1005/everyone","reputation":1798,"display_name":"Everyone","accept_rate":57},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"score":1,"post_id":2742,"edited":false,"creation_date":1340465384,"comment_id":3892,"body":"I think you would have to define the conditions. Even a single plant will vary in photosynthetic output over the course of a single day. Would maximal photosynthetic output be sufficient?"},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user560"},"score":0,"post_id":2742,"edited":false,"creation_date":1340470027,"comment_id":3894,"body":"It should also be clarified how exactly you define efficiency. Photosynthesis on a molecular level is likely highly efficient because the pigments exploit a quantum mechanical property called quantum coherence. On a macroscopic level, looking at the overall organism, there must certainly be a range of efficiency when measuring incident photons relative to carbon fixation."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef067cf09ffd3cc8f069bacec73c8202?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":222,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/222/david-lebauer","reputation":780,"display_name":"David LeBauer","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":2742,"edited":false,"creation_date":1340473176,"comment_id":3895,"body":"Define efficiency: carbon fixed per unit of what [h2o, nitrogen, light, CO2]? Any way you look at it, the answer will be &quot;no&qu