e is one study:<\/p>\n\n<p>Das B, Saini D, Seshadri M. Telomere length in human adults and high level natural background radiation. PLoS One. 2009 Dec 23;4(12):e8440.<\/p>\n\n<p>however I've seen similar studies published elsewhere.  Telomere length as diagnostic for age is very poor at best.  Here's an article that gives a formula, but acknowledges the R<sup>2<\/sup> is 0.04, which is useless: <a href=\"http://preview.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18378481\">http://preview.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18378481<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":331,"question_id":186,"up_vote_count":18,"last_edit_date":1325252429},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b9ab37a714c62cfdc39c2c57601c2cee?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1067,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1067/c0zmic","reputation":162,"display_name":"c0zmic"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":2766,"edited":false,"creation_date":1340791480,"comment_id":3943,"body":"It&#39;s always helpful to <a href=\"http://meta.biology.stackexchange.com/questions/276/how-to-link-to-scientific-articles-on-biology-se\">link to<\/a> papers you reference :-)"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1340791732,"creation_date":1340786965,"body":"<p>A number of studies have compared replicative capacity of cells with lifespan.  Since Replicative capacity of cells is linked to telomere-length, these studies may provide indirect evidence for the association between telomere length and lifespan.  One interesting study in particular compared animal life spans and in vitro replicative capacity of skin fibroblasts in groupings of small, middle, large, and very large breeds of dogs of specific ages (<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8914489\" rel=\"nofollow\">Li et al, 1996<\/a>). It was found that the life spans were inversely correlated to the frame sizes of the breeds. It was shown that all the small breeds studied have a longer life span than that of the large breeds. The replicative capacity of fibroblasts from the large dogs (Great Dane and Irish Wolfhound) was significantly decreased compared with that of the small dogs. The reasoning behind these observations may again be due to varying degrees of cell turnover between the species. Large dogs consist of more cells than small dogs and as a result more cell turnover was initially required in their development compared to small dogs. This increase in cell turnover would subsequently lead to a decrease in replicative potential (due to telomere shortening) and an increase in the rate of senescent cell formation.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2766,"question_id":186,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1340791732}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/186/is-telomere-length-a-reliable-measure-of-health-lifespan","last_activity_date":1340791732,"creation_date":1324152537,"answer_count":3,"title":"Is telomere length a reliable measure of health/lifespan?","body":"<p>Several companies are commercializing tests for telomere length such as this one <a href=\"http://www.telomehealth.com/index.html\">here<\/a>. I understand the basic mechanism for why telomeres shorten during DNA replication, but how good is the evidence that telomere length is a reliable indicator of healthspan/lifespan?<\/p>\n","question_id":186,"tags":["human-biology","dna","telomere"],"score":28,"accepted_answer_id":331,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":531,"up_vote_count":29},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3cfeec7dfb47b3d98c5edf17295e959b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":81,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/81/poshpaws","reputation":4731,"display_name":"Poshpaws","accept_rate":71},"answers":[{"owner":