 final volume of 7mL. And finaly draw an eight with the plate in the hood more than 3 times to mix them well.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Edit:<\/strong> For the addition of 10-50 cells, count these cells with trypan blue, and do a 1:100 dilution, for example if you have 1e6 cells in 10mL you could take 0.01 mL (10 microliters) to get 1, 000 cells <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/2QTk3.gif\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/I8vGT.gif\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>And then you add the 0.01mL into 1mL of cell media to get 1 cell per 1 microliter, and then if you wanna get 10 cells, take 10 microliters, and so on<\/p>\n","answer_id":2693,"question_id":2687,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1340123574}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2687/what-is-an-efficient-way-to-spike-10-50-cells-to-a-culture","last_activity_date":1340123574,"creation_date":1340049868,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is an efficient way to spike 10-50 cells to a culture","body":"<p>I'm trying to add on the order of 10-50 mammalian cells to a mixture of other cells (order of 1e6 cells). What is the best way to do this?<\/p>\n\n<p>(edit) I guess this wasn't clear. I would really like to emphasize how to sort 10-50 cells to give me an precise (not necessarily accurate but that would be nice too) method of getting a desired number of cells.<\/p>\n","question_id":2687,"tags":["cell-culture"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":87,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1340090523},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/561540fd593e30ae6b6180649b272bdb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":1031,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1031/luke-ocyte","reputation":38,"display_name":"Luke O'Cyte"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1f63c5adb465b6d33a480a3edc8b762d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"regis