,"body":"<p>I believe there are evidences in both directions in terms of mechanisms to favor variation in a population: outbreeding and crossing within individuals that look alike. There is a fine line between the two. Outbreeding helps in keeping variation and mixing variants that appeared in different parts of the population, but too much outbreeding can generate inviable offspring. Too much inbreeding also reduces viability. Certain plants have features that are selected to favor outbreeding and make inbreeding incompatible by rejecting incompatible (\"self\") pollen (<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-incompatibility_in_plants\" rel=\"nofollow\">self-incompatibility mechanisms<\/a>).<\/p>\n","answer_id":2694,"question_id":2678,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1340096271}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2678/features-in-individuals-causing-high-population-variation","last_activity_date":1340096271,"creation_date":1339970598,"answer_count":1,"title":"Features in individuals causing high population variation","body":"<p>As I understand it, a population with high variation is something sought after, since it makes the population better equipped to face a dynamic environment.  <\/p>\n\n<p>Then, I guess features in an individual which causes it's population's variation to be high, should be selected for (high mutation rate, other features.. ?).<\/p>\n\n<p>If so, does this manifest itself partly as individuals preferring to mate with individuals from another population? (With genetic difference within reason, perhaps a norm for a proffered genetic difference between individuals)<\/p>\n","question_id":2678,"tags":["evolution"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":70,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1340092681},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3cfeec7dfb47b3d98c5edf17295e959b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":81,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/81/poshpaws","reputation":4731,"display_name":"Poshpaws","accept_rate":71},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":69,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/69/rory-m","reputation":9094,"display_name":"Rory M","accept_rate":88},"score":13,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":1,"post_id":1108,"edited":false,"creation_date":1340037909,"comment_id":3747,"body":"+1 although Taq is the specific polymerase of <i>T. aquaticus<\/i>, I am not sure whether there are specific names for <i>M. kandleri<\/i> polymerase..."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1340044003,"creation_date":1329777924,"body":"<p><em>Methanopyrus kandleri<\/em> has been able to grow and proliferate at temperatures of up to 122°C when under around 20atm (<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1073/pnas.0712334105\" rel=\"nofollow\">Takai et. al. 2008<\/a>).  This was achieved in the lab but the theory should hold true for deep sea thermal vents.  Another strain of <em>M. kandleri<\/em> survived incubation to 130°C however was unable to reproduce at this temperature. <\/p>\n\n<p>One of the key adaptions for thermophiles is the selection towards an extremely thermo-stable copy of the enzyme DNA polymerase.  This allows DNA replication at high temperatures and is similar to the 'Taq' polymerase used in the polymer chain reaction in labs, derived from another thermophile, <em>Thermus aquaticus<\/em>.    <\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><strong>References<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1073/pnas.0712334105\" rel=\"nofollow\"> <strong>Takai K, Nakamura K, Toki T, Tsunogai U, Miyazaki M, Miyazaki J, Hirayama H, Nakagawa S, Nunoura T, Horikoshi K<\/