methylation is needed to help activate/repress certain genomic regions on top of other epigenomic marks when the genome is so vast that there is a need for an extra level of marking?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>It is used as a repressor because it inhibits  hydrogen bonding of transcription factors and the like. I have not heard of it functioning as an activator.<\/p>\n\n<p>There are also other uses for methylation, for example  newly synthesized DNA is hemimethylated - where the parent strand is methylated and the child one not. From this it can be determined which is the parent strand during DNA repair.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2682,"question_id":2680,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1340032171}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2680/dna-methylation-and-genome-size","last_activity_date":1340032171,"creation_date":1340028881,"answer_count":1,"title":"DNA methylation and genome size","body":"<p>Is there any relationship between DNA methylation as a level of stability to epigenetic states and genome size? For example, it is claimed that DNA methylation is not required for epigenetic stability in <em>Drosophila melanogaster<\/em> and yeast, both genomes much smaller than mammalian or plant genomes. Could it be that DNA methylation is needed to help activate/repress certain genomic regions on top of other epigenomic marks when the genome is so vast that there is a need for an extra level of marking? Is there any evidence along those lines?<\/p>\n","question_id":2680,"tags":["genomics","gene-regulation"],"score":6,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":110,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1340029958},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0