cns.nyu.edu/~nava/courses/psych_and_brain/pdfs/Stratton_1896.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Some preliminary experiments on vision without inversion of the retinal image<\/a> - the original article from 1896.  More recently (and for me disappointingly :L) a lot of doubt has been put onto the thought that the field of vision was corrected - people were still very much aware that the image was inverted even if they could deal with it <a href=\"http://bit.ly/oDIesU\" rel=\"nofollow\">The myth of upright vision. A psychophysical and functional imaging study of adaptation to inverting spectacles<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/72210ddde36978fe51ec56d6a865ce29?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":684,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/684/chris","reputation":138,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":1614,"edited":false,"creation_date":1333137723,"comment_id":2024,"body":"Thank you for your efforts. This article seems to point out we can function normally despite inverted vision, i.e. without (the return of) upright vision. So as stated in my first post, why bother with flipping images after the retina if we can deal with the input either way? And how do we know we do?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ab24c0e23c30888c23e2d4fe9991cf2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":57,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/57/jonsca","reputation":3367,"display_name":"jonsca","accept_rate":100},"score":5,"post_id":1614,"edited":false,"creation_date":1333145450,"comment_id":2028,"body":"Closely related question on <a href=\"http://cogsci.stackexchange.com/questions/337/why-would-the-brain-flip-the-images-perceived-by-your-eyes\">CogSci.SE<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c33b5588bbd268ce2680853ea79b1a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/231/mgkrebbs","reputation":3086,"display_name":"mgkrebbs"},"score":4,"post_id":1614,"edited":false,"creation_date":1333178148,"comment_id":2032,"body":"The question assumes there is something like a little projection screen inside the brain -- something that has an &quot;up&quot; and a &quot;down&quot;.  It&#39;s not like that; there are just an array of retinal cells transmitting pulses to a set of neurons.  Retinal cell A talks to neuron 1, cell B to neuron 2, etc.  neurons 1 and 2 are not physically arranged in space in a way that matters to image perception.  There is no little man in there watching a little screen.  See the CogSci question that jonsca linked to."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":1614,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c33b5588bbd268ce2680853ea79b1a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/231/mgkrebbs","reputation":3086,"display_name":"mgkrebbs"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1333211045,"comment_id":2039,"body":"@mgkrebbs: the retinotopic mapping of images in the visual cortex is very precise. There is no projection screen in the brain but the image is processed in a very precise spatial manner."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c33b5588bbd268ce2680853ea79b1a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/231/mgkrebbs","reputation":3086,"display_name":"mgkrebbs"},"score":0,"post_id":1614,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"edited":false,"creation_date":1333252956,"comment_id":2044,"body":"@nico: Of course the neurons maintain precise connection relationships with neurons carrying signals from spatially adjacent areas of the retina. Nevertheless, there is nothing about the arrangement that makes it &quot;upside down&quot; and thus requires further processing to &quot;flip&quot; it."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":1614,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c33b5588bbd268ce2680853ea79b1a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/231/mgkrebbs","reputation":3086,"display_name":"mgkrebbs"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1333258165,"comment_id":2045,"body":"@mgkrebbs: OK, we agree. I just misunderstood your previous comment :)."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/13f5a730dead005d0a3a947d3c09ab81?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":691,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/691/chm","reputation":553,"display_name":"CHM"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1333420264,"creation_date":1333420264,"body":"<p>I think you're oversimplifying the problem. Think about gravitation.<\/p>\n\n<p>Take this informal example: at any point on a massive sphere, you can define \"bottom\" such that any massive object with weight less than that of the sphere is subject to an attractive force towards that point. The direction of the force points in the direction of the \"bottom\".<\/p>\n\n<p>Assuming this holds true for every massive object, the following is logical: for the purpose of orientation, it is a lot more energy efficient for an organism to simply invert the image using brain circuitry than invert <em>every single sensory input<\/em> to effectively reverse the definition of \"bottom\", which follows from physical laws to which the organism is <em>invariably<\/em> bound.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1642,"question_id":1614,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6de105a59f6220973ef6029e8c55bb5f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":500,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/500/artem-kaznatcheev","reputation":1711,"display_name":"Artem Kaznatcheev","accept_rate":40},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":1,"post_id":2664,"edited":false,"creation_date":1339924236,"comment_id":3715,"body":"So is the retinotopic arrangement inverse top-to-bottom of the input from the retina? In that case it&#39;s still a valid question why the pathways from one half would at some point cross over with those from the other half and not just stay on the side they are."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":2664,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"edited":false,"creation_date":1339945290,"comment_id":3717,"body":"@Armatus: that is a different question from the &qu