bon fixation step, such as in CAM or C4 plants, if the net fixation measurement includes the intermediates - the pool of intermediate carbon-containing molecules have technically been fixed but not by RuBisCO. However, over longer time periods this effect will disappear, as ultimately all CO2 is fixed or re-fixed through RuBisCO.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2597,"question_id":1338,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1338/compare-and-contrast-rubisco-activity-and-assimilation-rate-is-there-a-diff","last_activity_date":1339509489,"creation_date":1331168448,"answer_count":1,"title":"Compare and contrast \"Rubisco activity\" and \"assimilation rate\" (is there a difference, and if so, what is it)?","body":"<p>I am confused about the variable \"RuBisCO activity\". How is it measured, and is it any different from the net assimilation rate?<\/p>\n\n<p>Based on some background reading (e.g. <a href=\"http://www.globalchange.umich.edu/globalchange1/current/lectures/kling/energyflow/energyflow.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Kling, 2008<\/a>; <a href=\"http://books.google.com/books?id=PXBq6jsT5SYC&amp;lpg=PA43&amp;dq=%22rubisco%20activity%22&amp;pg=PA43#v=onepage&amp;q=%22rubisco%20activity%22&amp;f=false\" rel=\"nofollow\">Lambers et al 2011<\/a>)  the only difference that I can find is the units. Both would have \"carbon fixed per unit time\", but RuBisCO activity is expressed per unit mass of the enzyme, while assimilation rate is per unit leaf area (or less commonly, leaf mass).<\/p>\n","question_id":1338,"tags":["plant-physiology","enzymes","photosynthesis","ecology"],"score":7,"accepted_answer_id":2597,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":286,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1331206362},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a19967ad1671dd3bdea616a17a2fb0a1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":868,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/868/zsub","reputation":133,"display_name":"Zsub"},