t mean it makes much sense to do so. <em>E. coli<\/em> in particular have been used as bench tools for decades: lots of protocols exist for using them in the lab, their genome has been extensively sequenced and is well studied, and they're cheap. I'm not a bench biologist anymore, but I'm guessing these are the reasons they stripped living bacteria and replaced their DNA rather than trying to build a completely synthetic microbe from scratch.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1583,"question_id":1579,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1332866315},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3ffe58764027b260fbdb927b79b3e6f6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":929,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/929/elisabeth","reputation":91,"display_name":"Elisabeth"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1338913027,"creation_date":1338913027,"body":"<p>There is this guy, Martin Hanczyc, working on protocells to better understand how the beginning of life occurred. He makes synthetic protocells. They don't have any DNA in them but they are pretty cool and maybe the beginnings to making synthetic cells. Perhaps once science has figured out how cells began and their very minimal needs they can create completely synthetic cells.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ted.com/talks/martin_hanczyc_the_line_between_life_and_not_life.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ted.com/talks/martin_hanczyc_the_line_between_life_and_not_life.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Also, just thinking, what would we consider completely synthetic cells? If we took synthetic protocells and they eventually evolved into a cell with DNA would that still be synthetic? <\/p>\n","answer_id":2504,"question_id":1579,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1579/synthetic-biology-using-existing-cells","last_activity_date":1338913027,"creation_date":1332852637,"answer_count":2,"title":"Synthetic biology using existing cells","body":"<p>I was watching the video at this link:\n<a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-17436365\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-17436365<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>The speaker says that a cell is taken and its original DNA content is stripped out and replaced with synthetic DNA.<\/p>\n\n<p>Does this mean scientists are not able to create a synthetic cell yet? Is this why they use existing cells, stripping them out and replacing the DNA?<\/p>\n","question_id":1579,"tags":["dna","cell-biology","synthetic-biology"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":1583,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":101,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1332864461},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cff3e84bcedd40163c74d33b827ac7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/307/lancelafontaine","reputation":3814,"display_name":"LanceLafontaine","accept_rate":47},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0a3069491bfded90cdf623341cadc1d1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":471,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/471/manishearth","reputation":101,"display_name":"Manishearth"},"score":1,"post_id":2489,"edited":false,"creation_date":1338822925,"comment_id":3431,"body":"IIRC there&#39;s no &quot;accepted&quot; one--depending upon the enzyme, it can be either."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/95137280522b04ea050f00bc6398356b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":956,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/956/blues","reputation":431,"display_name":"blues"},"score":8,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cff3e84bcedd40163c74d33b827ac7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/307/lancelafontaine","reputation":3814,"display_name":"LanceLafontaine","accept_rate":47},"score":0,"post_id":2490,"edited":false,"creation_date":1338825868,"comment_id":3433,"body":"Thanks for the answer, like mention of continuum. I&#39;ll wait to see if there are more answers before I accept though."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1338826124,"creation_date":1338825679,"body":"<p>This is true of all protein binding as well as the special case of enzyme-substrate interaction:<\/p>\n\n<p>Various proteins are more dynamic than others: some have only one or two overall conformations and are relatively implastic otherwise. An example would be a receptor tyrosine kinase like Kit (or CD117, or Mast Stem Cell Growth Factor Receptor, whatever you want to call it), which has a very stable structure and binds its substrates in a lock and key manner.<\/p>\n\n<p>Others, for example p53 (not an enzyme), have much more structural placiticity - even to the point of being mostly disordered when not bound. They tend to be induced fit binders (of other proteins, not catalytic substrates) and often exploit that to bind a broader range of possible targets than lock and key proteins.<\/p>\n\n<p>The point is, it is a continuum between lock and key &lt;-----> induced fit rather than discrete classes you can sort proteins into.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2490,"question_id":2489,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1338826124},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/222b478bab6d59dc5de514a87dba88cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":389,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/389/bobthejoe","reputation":4911,"display_name":"bobthejoe","accept_rate":53},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1338839594,"creation_date":1338839594,"body":"<p>Both models are true depending on how you frame the mechanisms of catalysis. As mentioned by @Blues, proteins are highly dynamic. In that manner, a protein will adopt both the unbound active state shown in the induced fit model and the complementary shape shown in the lock and key model. <\/p>\n\n<p>(apologies since this is the only figure that I could find to explain this concept). Using the above description the induced fit model (E) will change its structure to the E*S model. In the lock and key model, the E state will be equivalent to the E*S state. According to the below figure, this would imply that the E*S state always exists but as it is a few kcals higher in free energy, the state is rarely seen. Thermodynamically, this means that the \"lock\" always exists but it is an unstable configuration. When the substrate is added to the system, it will stablize the lock and thermodynamically favor an E*S state.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/cmqgv.gif\" alt=\"Thermodynamics\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Long story short, the induced fit model is a good explanation of how enzymes morph into an active state but depending on how you frame the mechanism, you are always seeing a lock-key model (at least according to my enzymology professor). Unfortunately, the majority of biochemistry textbook continue to teach using the induced fit model since it is a much easier concept to understand given the majority of undergrads; and 1st year graduates' understanding of statistical thermodynamics.<\/p>\n\n<p>The induced fit model is more appropriately used to understand the mechanisms of substrate specificity. As hinted by your professor, enzymes will perform their function in the lock-key mechanism. This is true for many serine proteases which all do the exact same reaction. However, substrate specificity can be incorporated by unstabilizing the E*S complex which largely has to do with the E state.<\/p>\n","answer_id":2494,"question_id":2489,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2489/what-is-the-correct-model-for-enzyme-substrate-complementarity","last_activity_date":1338839594,"creation_date":1338821465,"answer_count":2,"title":"What is the correct model for enzyme-substrate complementarity?","body":"<p><a href=\"http://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Structural_Biochemistry/Enzyme/Active_Site#Models\">This Wikibook<\/a> shows both proposed models of enzyme-substrate complementarity, the Lock and Key model and the Induced Fit model. I've always been taught that the Induced Fit model is  the proper one. However, my biochemistry professor mentioned that often times, enzymes behave as lock and key. I also noticed that the Wikibook doesn't mention which model is in fact true.<\/p>\n\n<p><em>The Lock and Key Model<\/em>\n<img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ekkPN.jpg\" alt=\"The Lock and Key Model\"><\/p>\n\n<p><em>The Induced Fit Model<\/em>\n<img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/cBJ47.jpg\" alt=\"The Induced Fit Model\"><\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Is there currently one accepted model? Which is it, and why?<\/strong><\/p>\n","question_id":2489,"tags":["biochemistry","enzymes","binding-sites"],"score":6,"accepted_answer_id":2490,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":2920,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1338821904},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f122990dd51c351f3c24fcef7e5ca0d1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":957,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/957/andrei-kucharavy","reputation":205,"display_name":"Andrei Kucharavy"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/222b478bab6d59dc5de514a87dba88cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":389,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/389/bobthejoe","reputation":4911,"display_name":"bobthejoe","accept_rate":53},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f122990dd51c351f3c24fcef7e5ca0d1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":957,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/957/andrei-kucharavy","reputation":205,"display_name":"Andrei Kucharavy"},"score":0,"post_id":2492,"edited":false,"creation_da